Wages are so stagnant that people can hardly afford groceries; Target recently (basically) admitted that, "yeah, we inflated our prices for funsies" and now they're deflating them because of all the complaints about people being unable to afford shit. And this is what you're talking about? THIS is the most important thing you think you could possibly talk about at this point in time?! There are families in Gaza that don't exist anymore! There are entire genealogical pools that have been *wiped off the face of the earth*. There are people in Rafa begging for help. We are watching the wholesale destruction, slaughter and eradication of an entire people group; but you think strangers' genitals and which bathrooms they should use is the most important thing we can be fucking discussing right now?! What rock do you live under? What do you smoke? What do you drink? Because I would love some. I would love to be so detached and delusional and completely unaware of the world around me, so that I can be just as oblivious and focus on things that don't matter, just like you. I would love that! But no, instead, I wake up every day thinking about Palestine and how I'm unable to fucking help anybody because I'm broke, how all of my money has to go to rent, otherwise I will end up homeless. My thoughts are consumed about the deteriorating life of every American in this country, and how we are just watching a genocide happen in full goddamn view of everyone and God,  and you are sitting on your butt, in your bathroom, with your 4 inch baby pink acrylics, talking about genitals!! I think what hurts me the most is that there are so many people just like you, who literally don't give a darn about how the average American is this close to homelessness with every paycheck, and how there's entire families just gone, off the face of the planet. I hate you, but in a way I envy you. I envy the fact that you can hear all of this shit going on, hear about the misery and the frustrations and the unhappiness, and still be wholly consumed by whether or not somebody has a weenie. I don't know how.. but somehow I envy that.

And I really don't think that we should be using the bystander effect. As kind of a reason to explain what is or is not happening. Like regarding response in Gaza, this is more of, like a collective action problem. It's more of a misinformation and disinformation problem. Like, people know what's happening, and people are acting. So, like, even now with Gaza, it's not that we're all standing around looking at each other. This is a problem that is due to poor coordination. It is a lack of communication laterally among ourselves. voice_to_text: A major new poll released by Axio shows that college students don't really care about the protests that are ongoing on campuses. A survey over 12 college students show that the conflict in the Middle East was only cared about by 13% of those survey. These numbers aren't really surprising at all. This movement is a mess. Part of what is causing the problem is this movement is surprisingly ineffective at using social media. Instead of using it to raise sympathy for their cause, it's mainly being used to give the movement itself a false impression of how popular this movement is, and then to bully people who question the movement itself. This kind of echo chamber. You can maintain the belief that it's everyone else that's failing, when really it's the movement itself that's failing on every level. But rather than dwell on the failures, let's talk about solutions. The goal of any movement like this is to raise awareness and sympathy for your cause and to turn that sympathy into action. Problem with taking direct actions like encampments, destroying property, disrupting civic life, and then making hostage like demands to get you to stop, is you push more people away than you pull in. Actions themselves create fear and anger, which are both antithetical to sympathy and can inadvertently create sympathy for the opposing cause. There's another approach called a dilemma action, which is an indirect, non aggressive form of protest where the goal is to provoke a dilemma. For the opposition, where they look absurd no matter how they respond. For example, in 1982, in response to Soviet propaganda, Polish citizens started taking their televisions for walks, and wheelbarrows and strollers during the Soviet news hours. This created a situation where the government would have to arrest people for walking their television, which would then be covered in the news itself, creating the dilemma. Not only would it look absurd, but they'd have to explain why people were walking their televisions, exposing their own propaganda and spreading the message of the protesters. For them, cause of that dilemma, the government didn't do anything, which conceded ground to the Polish resistance movement, enabling them to broaden support for resisting the Soviet system. George Washington University recently used this technique against the protesters, when they hung a huge American flag in the backdrop of the protests. And the contrast put the protesters in a really negative way, while maintaining the integrity of the university. As standing up for the rights of all. Which increase their support to resist the protesters. The reason this work is because of your movement is only focus on what you're going to do and how you can express your English to your audience. It becomes self absorbed. I think we're seeing a lot of that, which is why they become blind. How antisocial this movement has become. But if you're thinking in terms of a dilemma action, you're thinking of your social movement as a Social interaction between you, your opposition, and most importantly, the rest of society. Society is the audience. They are the people you're trying to convince. They are the ones holding the sympathy that you need. But here's the question. How do you do that? What does a dilemma action look like for this movement? Let's hear some suggestions in the comments.
